        },
        {
            "endOffset": 110097,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec6",
            "sentence": "Combining the results in this section, we obtain the following main theorem:",
            "startOffset": 110021,
            "title": "Conditions on the blocks of a graph"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 79832,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b9": {
                    "endOffset": 79746,
                    "startOffset": 79743
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "In 1966, Gallai [9] asked whether every graph contains a vertex that belongs to all of its longest paths.",
            "startOffset": 79727,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 80001,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "There are graphs such that, for every vertex, we can find a longest path that does not contain that vertex.",
            "startOffset": 79894,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 83419,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec2",
            "sentence": "In this section, we present definitions and establish the notation that is going to be used in the next sections.",
            "startOffset": 83306,
            "title": "Definitions and notation"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 80472,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b18": {
                    "endOffset": 80419,
                    "startOffset": 80415
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "Such graphs are called hypotraceable graphs and Thomassen [18] proved that there exists an infinite number of them.",
            "startOffset": 80357,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 80356,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "This is the case, for instance, of graphs that do not contain a hamiltonian path and in which the deletion of any vertex results in a traceable graph, that is, a graph that contains a hamiltonian path.",
            "startOffset": 80155,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 82395,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b16": {
                    "endOffset": 82306,
                    "startOffset": 82302
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "This example was given by Schmitz [16], who proved that there is no vertex that belongs to all the longest paths of this graph.",
            "startOffset": 82268,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 82514,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b19": {
                    "endOffset": 82513,
                    "startOffset": 82509
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "In fact, it is known that infinitely many planar 3-connected cubic graphs answer negatively to Gallai\u2019s question [19].",
            "startOffset": 82396,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 83305,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec2",
            "sentence": "Throughout the paper, the graphs considered are simple and connected.",
            "startOffset": 83236,
            "title": "Definitions and notation"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 80062,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b20": {
                    "endOffset": 80061,
                    "startOffset": 80057
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "The first example of such a graph was given by Walther [20].",
            "startOffset": 80002,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 80154,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "b17": {
                    "endOffset": 80152,
                    "startOffset": 80148
                }
            },
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "In fact, there are infinitely many graphs for which this holds (for an overview, see [17]).",
            "startOffset": 80063,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 79726,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "It is well known that, in any connected graph, every pair of longest paths always shares a common vertex.",
            "startOffset": 79621,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 82267,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "sec1",
            "sentence": "Among the graph classes for which the answer to Gallai\u2019s question is not affirmative are planar graphs and bipartite graphs, as can be seen from the graph in Fig. 1.",
            "startOffset": 82102,
            "title": "Introduction"
        }
